FIGURE.name: Figure AI
FIGURE.tagline: Building the world's first commercially viable general-purpose humanoid robot to address the global labor shortage
FIGURE.overview: Figure AI is a Sunnyvale, California-based robotics company founded in 2022 by serial entrepreneur Brett Adcock. The company is developing general-purpose humanoid robots designed to address global labor shortages in warehousing, logistics, and manufacturing. Figure assembled its team from robotics experts from Boston Dynamics, Tesla, Google DeepMind, and Apple. In September 2025, Figure exceeded $1 billion in Series C funding at a $39 billion post-money valuation, making it one of the most valuable robotics startups in history. The company partnered with BMW for real-world testing at their Spartanburg plant, where Figure 02 robots demonstrated 400% speed improvements and 7x success rate gains in manufacturing tasks.

products.name: Figure 03
products.description: Third-generation humanoid with complete hardware/software redesign, 60% wider field of view, palm cameras, and tactile sensors detecting forces as small as 3 grams (Oct 2025)

products.name: Figure 02 with Helix
products.description: 1.68m tall, 60kg, 25kg lift capacity, 6 RGB cameras, 16 DoF hands, 5+ hour battery runtime, 3x computing power with NVIDIA RTX GPUs

products.name: Helix VLA Model
products.description: Vision-language-action neural network: System 2 at 7-9 Hz for high-level planning, System 1 at 200 Hz for real-time control, full upper-body coordination

products.name: BotQ Manufacturing Facility
products.description: California-based factory capable of producing 12,000 humanoids/year, robots building robots, injection molding in 20 seconds vs week on CNC

products.name: Figure 01
products.description: Original prototype for logistics and warehousing, demonstrated at BMW factory in Spartanburg, SC

products.name: Custom AI Partnership
products.description: Collaboration with OpenAI (now ended) for conversational capabilities; developing in-house AI models

highlights.text: Raised $1B+ Series C at $39B valuation (Sep 2025) led by Parkway Venture Capital
Unveiled BotQ manufacturing facility targeting 12,000 robots/year production (Mar 2025)
Announced Helix vision-language-action model for generalist humanoid control (Feb 2025)
Ended OpenAI collaboration; LLMs becoming "smarter yet more commoditized" (2025)
Raised $675M Series B at $2.6B valuation with Microsoft, NVIDIA, Jeff Bezos, OpenAI (Feb 2024)
Brett Adcock named to TIME's 100 Most Influential People in AI 2024
BMW tests Figure 02 at Spartanburg plant – 400% faster, 7x better success rate
Plan to ship 100,000 humanoids over the next four years

FANATICS.name: Fanatics
FANATICS.tagline: Global digital sports platform operating licensed merchandise, trading cards collectibles, sports betting, and live commerce businesses
FANATICS.overview: Fanatics, Inc. is an American sports merchandise and technology company founded by Michael Rubin in 1995. The company has evolved from a licensed apparel retailer into a diversified digital sports platform spanning Commerce (77% of revenue), Collectibles/Trading Cards (20%), and Sports Betting (4%). In 2024, Fanatics generated $8.1 billion in revenue (up 15% YoY) and expects to be EBITDA profitable in 2025. Fanatics Collectibles has shown remarkable growth, with revenue jumping 40% to $1.6 billion after acquiring Topps in 2022. The company's valuation ranges from $17-31 billion on secondary markets, down from its $31 billion peak in 2022.

FLEXPORT.name: Flexport
FLEXPORT.tagline: Making global trade easy for everyone through technology-powered freight forwarding
FLEXPORT.overview: Flexport is a digital freight forwarding and supply chain platform founded in 2013 by Ryan Petersen. The company provides technology-enabled logistics services including ocean, air, and truck freight. Flexport's valuation fell to $3.8B in 2024 (down from $8B peak in 2022) after freight rates normalized post-COVID. Revenue rebounded 30% to $2.1B in 2024 from a $1.6B low in 2023 (down from $5B peak in 2022). In 2023, Flexport acquired Shopify's logistics operations, making Shopify a 17% stakeholder. The company expects to be 'quite profitable' by end of 2025.

products.name: Flexport Platform
products.description: End-to-end supply chain visibility and management

products.name: Ocean Freight
products.description: Full container load and less-than-container shipping

highlights.text: Expects to be 'quite profitable' by end 2025

FAIRE.name: Faire
FAIRE.tagline: Connecting independent retailers with unique brands to build thriving local economies
FAIRE.overview: Faire is a wholesale marketplace founded in 2017 by Max Rhodes, Jeff Hamilton, Daniele Perito, and Marcelo Cortes. The platform connects independent retailers with unique brands, enabling boutiques to discover and purchase wholesale inventory. In November 2025, Faire launched a $5.2B tender offer for employee liquidity—down 59% from its $12.6B peak valuation in 2022. Revenue exceeds $500M annualized with $3B GMV expected in 2025. Faire serves 800K+ retailers and 100K+ brands globally, growing 40% YoY.
